rnment-proposed programs, similarly to how the Congressional Budget Office =
scores proposals, only in a more broadly accessible way. In any event, the =
O.M.B. gig didn=E2=80=99t work out; at the time, Marc couldn=E2=80=99t easi=
ly disentangle himself from his various Apollo obligations and conflicts.

Eight years later, for whatever reasons, Marc was
better able to make himself available. During their chat, Marc expressed hi=
s belief that there was a chance for =E2=80=9Cfundamental change,=E2=80=9D =
a chance to =E2=80=9Cdo everything you want to do, but do it in a smart way=
=2E=E2=80=9D Smart tariffs. Smart depor=
tation. =E2=80=9CYou can make this bet=
ter,=E2=80=9D Marc told him, according to someone familiar with that conver=
sation. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m rooting for you.=E2=80=9D

In Marc=E2=80=99s view, the election offered a stark choice. In his mind, T=
rump=E2=80=99s return to the Oval Office was an =E2=80=9Cuncertain death,=
=E2=80=9D yes, but it was far preferable to the =E2=80=9Ccertain death=E2=
=80=9D of electing Kamala Harris=E2=80=94the choice between fear of change =
or fear of more of the status quo, and for him, the Biden-Harris status quo=
 wasn=E2=80=99t working for the country. (It has worked for him personally,=
 of course; he=E2=80=99s worth around $10 billion these days.)

