He=E2=80=99s the kind of guy who wonders why we spend more on education tha=
n any other country but our students rank among the most poorly educated in=
 the developed world. Or why we spend more on healthcare but our life expec=
tancy continues to decline. He believes what we=E2=80=99re doing is not wor=
king, so why be afraid of someone who is focused on blowing it up and pushi=
ng for wholesale change? He thinks that Trump Unleashed=E2=80=94a second-te=
rm president beholden to no one for reelection=E2=80=94has a chance to effe=
ct real change.

Marc also thinks, I=E2=80=99m told, that there=E2=80=99s a real chance for =
Trump II to fix things for the better, that America is still a force for go=
od in the world, and that it just requires us to think and do things differ=
ently and to be willing to take chances. He was =E2=80=9Cso happy to see Tr=
ump elected over Kamala,=E2=80=9D according to the person
familiar with Marc=E2=80=99s thinking.

Realpolitik

Rowan is not naive about politics. He subscribes to the recently espoused t=
hinking of UFC C.E.O. Dana White, a key Trump supporter, who told The New Y=
orker, about politics, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m never fucking doing this again.=
 I want nothing to do with this shit. It=E2=80=99s gross. It=E2=80=99s disg=
usting.=E2=80=9D Marc=E2=80=99s view is that politics is a dirty sport=E2=
=80=94that everyone plays dirty, and that Trump doesn=E2=80=99t play any di=
rtier than anyone else. It=E2=80=99s just that the mainstream media doesn=
=E2=80=99t like the Trump brand of playing dirty but is okay with, say, the=
 prosecutions against Trump initiated by Letitia James and Alvin Bragg. But=
 the Trump brand of politics is what the country wants now, as evidenced by=
 his slim but definitive majority of the popular vote and his decisive Elec=
toral College win.

In the end, Marc didn=E2=80=99t get the nod
to be treasury secretary. It went, instead, to Scott Bessent, the hedge fun=
d manager who was probably the leading candidate all along. Marc had heard =
from enough people between Wednesday and Friday night, when Trump made the =
decision, to know that he wasn=E2=80=99t going to be the choice. He=E2=80=
=99s okay with that. He was just thrilled to be considered, a middle-class =
kid from Merrick, Long Island, who made it big on Wall Street and almost go=
t offered a big job in Washington.

In any event, it was back to business as usual this weekend at Apollo. On S=
unday, Marc was driving to his office at 9 West 57th Street to meet with hi=
s two key deputies, Scott Kleinman and Jim Zelter. After all, it=E2=80=99s =
bonus time on Wall Street, and no matter how broken Marc thinks the country=
 is, Apollo generated billions in 2024, and it falls on the three men to di=
vvy up the spoils.

As he was leaving Mar-a-Lago last Wednesday after his meeting with Trump, h=
e ran into
Don Jr., whom he=E2=80=99d never met before. He also ran into Bessent. It w=
as time to celebrate their collective good fortune. Tequila shots all aroun=
d. And then it was back on the private jet to New York City for Marc and ba=
ck to the business of running Apollo.

